What is kmeans? ¶

kmeans is a popular unsupervised machine learning algorithm used for clustering data into a specified number of clusters.

Data groups which are similar are known as clusters. kmeans algorithm is based on calculating centroids of these clusters and assigning data closest to these centroids to the respective clusters.

In this algorithm, the initial centroids are randomly assigned. With each iteration, the mean of the points of each centroid is computed and the centroids are shifted to the mean. Hence the name "kmeans".

The clusters are iteratively computed until the clusters do not change. This is the stopping point of the algorithm.

Image source: https://stanford.edu/~cpiech/cs221/handouts/kmeans.html

kmeans++¶

kmeans++ is a variation of the kmeans algorithm in which the centroids are not randomly initialized. In this algorithm, the cluster centroids are chosen in a smarter way.

The crux of this algorithm is to choose the centroids such that they are farthest apart. Essentially, we must be choosing a centroid that has the maximum of the minimum distance to existing centroids.

Once these centroids are chosen according to the kmeans++ algorithm, the process is exactly the same as kmeans to choose the clusters.

Simple one feature case¶

Let's first take a simple example of a 1 feature dataset. Here we have the grades of students and we want to bucket it to 3 clusters. From the clusters formed, we identify that similar grades have been put together and the centroids are indicative of what the three score buckets look like.

def plot(centroids,y_km):
    # plot the 3 clusters
    plt.scatter(
        X[y_km == 0, 0], X[y_km == 0, 1],
        s=50, c='green',
        marker='s', edgecolor='black',
        label='cluster 1'
    )

    plt.scatter(
        X[y_km == 1, 0], X[y_km == 1, 1],
        s=50, c='yellow',
        marker='o', edgecolor='black',
        label='cluster 2'
    )

    plt.scatter(
        X[y_km == 2, 0], X[y_km == 2, 1],
        s=50, c='blue',
        marker='v', edgecolor='black',
        label='cluster 3'
    )

    # plot the centroids
    plt.scatter(
        centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1],
        s=250, marker='*',
        c='red', edgecolor='black',
        label='centroids'
    )
    plt.legend(scatterpoints=1)
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

The algorithm ¶

These are the steps I followed to implement these algorithms: ( here X is the given data to be clustered and k is the number of clusters) For kmeans:

1. For given k, initialize k random centroid points from given X points
2. For each point in X, find the centroid closest to X and assign said point to the cluster
3. With the newly formed clusters, compute the new centroid as a mean of the cluster points for that centroid
4. Iterate until the clusters do not change (centroids remain the same)

For kmeans++:

1. Pick the first centroid at random.
2. Pick the next centroid such that the minimum distance to the existing cluster centroids is maximized. 
3. Iterate to find the next k-1 centroids. 
4. The rest of the algorithm is the same as kmeans

How to choose k?¶

Often we may not know the ideal number of clusters to be selected as the data is unknown and we don't have any idea of the labels or how many groups can exist. In such a scenario we must choose a k-value based on other computational methods.

Optimal value of k can be chosen using the "elbow method". In this method, the squared errors are calculated for each point by computing the distance from a point to the assigned cluster. The overall sum of squares is compared for a set of k values and the k with lowest square errors is chosen as optimal.

Another method to determine k value is using "silhouette method" which computes the similaraity between points in same cluster vs other clusters. k value with a high silhoutte score is chosen as optimal k.

image source :https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/how-to-determine-the-optimal-k-for-k-means-708505d204eb

Applications¶

In the data sciene industry kmeans is widely using for the following:

  • Document Classification
  • Fraud detection
  • Customer Segmentation
  • Crime profiling

For any typical data science problem, we can use clustering to create new features to train our model.

Below, we discuss another interesting application which is image compression.

Image Compression ¶

Here we will use kmeans to compress greyscale and colour images

Greyscale¶

In [193]:
import matplotlib.image as mpimg
img = mpimg.imread('example3.jpeg')
imgplot = plt.imshow(img)
print("Original Image:")
plt.show()

Original Image:
In [225]:
X = img.reshape(-1,1)
k=4
centroids, clusters = kmeans(X, k=k,tolerance=.01)
centroids = centroids.astype(np.uint8)
m = np.zeros(X.shape)
for i,j in enumerate(clusters):
    m[j] = centroids[i] 
new = m.reshape(img.shape)
print("Compressed Image:")
imgplot = plt.imshow(new.astype('uint8'))

Compressed Image:

With just 4 of the greyscale levels, the above image still looks recognizable after the compression!

Spectral Clustering ¶

Another popular clustering algorithm is spectral clustering. It is particulrly useful when the shapes of clusters are not spherical (like in kmeans since it uses the mean to compute the groups)

Spectral clustering involves creating a similarity graph and uses a kmeans model with eigenvectors as inputs.

image source: https://towardsdatascience.com/unsupervised-machine-learning-spectral-clustering-algorithm-implemented-from-scratch-in-python-205c87271045
